TEC, Inc. has been retained by Cresset Groves, LLC to prepare a Traffic Impact, Access, and
Parking Study (TIAPS) associated with a proposed redevelopment of the former General Electric
(GE) Water and Process Technologies Building at 65 Grove Street in Watertown, Massachusetts.
The study has been prepared to provide a comprehensive evaluation of traffic and parking
characteristics for the existing site and the proposed project.
The existing GE Water and Process Technologies Building at 65 Grove Street is currently vacant
and consists of an existing three-story ±134,455 square foot (SF) mixed-use structure, which
previously contained ±81,135 SF of general office space and ±53,320 SF of research &
development space. The site previously accommodated ±200 on-site parking stalls as shown in
Image 1 on the following page. The GE building previously employed 350 staff on a single shift
and the existing parking supply on site was not able to accommodate the parking demand for
these employees. As such, a large percentage of the former employees parked off-site, due to
a lack of available parking, within the neighborhood along Nichols Avenue, Crawford Street, and
The project consists of removing the two-story brick warehouse structure, converting all space
within the remaining ±122,470 SF building to general office space, and constructing a new
parking garage directly adjacent to the southerly edge of the remaining building structure to
accommodate a total of 349 parking spaces on site. The project will result in a net decrease in
total gross square footage while increasing the on-site parking to fully-accommodate all vehicles
on-site and eliminate employee parking in the surrounding residential neighborhood.
Access to the existing facility is provided via an entrance-only driveway along Grove Street east
of Arlington Street and via two full-access/egress driveways on Crawford Street which are
currently gated. As part of the project, access/egress will be maintained via the existing
driveway locations. The Grove Street driveway will remain one-way entrance-only, while the
two Crawford Street driveways will be converted to one-way flow. The direction of flow on

TEC has evaluated the traffic operations for the site driveways and study area intersections
under existing and future conditions. The future year planning horizon examines traffic

operations in the area after the project is complete.

Traffic growth is a function of the expected land development in the immediate area and the
surrounding region. Several methods can be used to estimate this growth. Traffic engineers
frequently employ an annual percentage increase in traffic growth, which is applied to all traffic
volumes under study. The drawback to such a procedure is that some turning volumes may
actually grow at either a higher or a lower rate at particular intersections.
An alternative procedure identifies the location and type of planned development, estimates the
traffic to be generated, and assigns it to the area roadway network. This procedure produces a
more realistic estimate of growth for local traffic. However, the drawback of this procedure is
that the potential growth in population and development external to the study area would not
be accounted for in the traffic projections.
To provide a conservative analysis framework, both procedures were considered.

A primary result of capacity analyses is the assignment of level-of-service to traffic facilities
The concept of level-of-service is defined as a qualitative
measure describing operational conditions within a traffic stream and their perception by motor-
ists and/or passengers. A level-of-service definition provides an index to quality of traffic flow
in terms of such factors as speed, travel time, freedom to maneuver, traffic interruptions, com-
Six levels of service are defined for each type of facility. They are given letter designations
from A to F, with level-of-service (LOS) A representing the best operating conditions and LOS F
representing the worst. Since the level of service of a traffic facility is a function of the traffic
flows placed upon it, such a facility may operate at a wide range of levels of service, depending
on the time of day, day of week, or period of year.

The capacity and queue analysis indicates long delays for vehicles turning left from Arlington
Street northbound onto Grove Street during the weekday morning and evening peak hours
under all analysis conditions. However, the signalized intersection of Mount Auburn Street /
Grove Street and the traffic direction officer at the Grove Street / Tufts Driveway create gaps in
traffic along Grove Street that allow vehicles to exit Arlington Street, which are not modeled in
the Synchro software analysis. Therefore, actual delays on Arlington Street are anticipated to
be significantly lower than modeled by the analysis software. However, the analysis software
may be used as a tool to measure the incremental impacts of the project in terms of increases
in delay. As shown in Table 7, the introduction of two-way traffic flow or reversal of one-way
flow on Crawford Street is expected to result in minor increases in delay for traffic turning left
from Arlington Street northbound onto Grove Street.
Traffic exiting Kondazian Street onto Grove Street is anticipated to operate at LOS F during the
weekday evening peak hour under 2019 Build conditions. However, the volume-to-capacity
(V/C) ratio will be below 1.00, indicating there will be adequate capacity to accommodate the
anticipated traffic volumes. With introduction of two-way traffic flow or reversal of one-way
flow on Crawford Street, this movement will operate at LOS E, with a reduction in delay of
approximately 54 seconds per vehicle and reduction in queues of six (6) vehicles.
Although the Grove Street northbound and southbound approaches experience delay during the
weekday morning and evening peak periods, the additional traffic generated by the proposed
redevelopment is not expected to increase delays by more than one second per vehicle or
increase queues by more than one vehicle on any approach. This level of impact does not
warrant project-specific mitigation at this intersection.

page.text: The Arlington Street southbound left-turn movement currently operates as a protected-only
phase, although only 9 to 17 vehicles are projected to make this left-turn movement during the

movements at the intersection are stopped with the exception of the Arlington Street
southbound through movement. Delay through the intersection could be significantly reduced
by eliminating this protected left-turn phase. This could be accomplished by either allowing this
movement to operate as permitted only (similar to the northbound approach) or by restricting
left-turns on this approach. As shown in Table 7, eliminating the protected left-turn phase and
optimizing the signal timing, the overall intersection delay will improve by 8 seconds per vehicle
and all movements will operate at acceptable levels of service (LOS D or better).
Reverse One-Way Flow on Crawford Street
Currently Crawford Street provides one-way flow in the eastbound direction away from the
Arlington Street / Nichols Avenue / Coolidge Hill Road / Crawford Street intersection. This
traffic flow would force all of the traffic exiting the 65 Grove Street site through the Crawford
Street and Kondazian Street neighborhood. By reversing the direction of travel on Crawford
Street, a large portion of this traffic would be redistributed to exit via the signalized Arlington
Street / Nichols Avenue / Coolidge Hill Road / Crawford Street intersection and would no longer
travel through the neighborhood. To accommodate the reversal of traffic flow on Crawford
Street, an additional signal phase would need to be added at the Arlington Street / Nichols
Avenue / Coolidge Hill Road / Crawford Street intersection. As shown in Table 7, with the
addition of this signal phase and optimizing the signal timing, the overall intersection delay is
anticipated to increase (degrade) by less than two second per vehicle during the weekday
morning peak hour and by approximately 14 seconds per vehicle during the weekday evening
peak hour. Despite a minor increase in delay, all movements will operate at LOS E or better
and volume-to-capacity (v/c) ratios well below 1.00, indicating there will be adequate capacity
to accommodate the anticipated traffic volumes.

page.text: Currently, the Watertown Greenway runs from School Street and terminates at the intersection

proposed to continue north through the signalized intersection as part of a future rail-trail
project. Bicycle traffic may significantly increase through the intersection with extension of the
Greenway and will need to be accommodated by the traffic signal. One option would be to
have bicyclists dismount their bicycles and cross the intersection during the exclusive pedestrian
phase using the striped crosswalks. An alternative would be to implement a dedicated bicycle
phase at the intersection to allow bicyclists to remain on their bicycles and cross the
intersection during a dedicated phase while all other movements are stopped. TEC has
performed a supplemental analysis to assess the impacts of providing a dedicated phase for the
Watertown Greenway at the signalized intersection. The results are summarized in Table 8 and
the detailed analysis worksheets are provided in Attachment K.

The Atrium School is located to the immediate east of the 65 Grove Street Redevelopment site,
and is accessed via an entrance-only driveway on Crawford Street and an exit-only driveway on
Grove Street just east of the 65 Grove Street driveways. An additional driveway is provided on
Kondazian Street north of Crawford Street to a parking lot for the Atrium School athletic fields.
Parents park along Crawford Street and Kondazian Street in the afternoon to pick up their
School begins at 8:15 AM for grades K-5 and at 8:30 AM for grades 6-8. During this time,
parents enter the school via Crawford Street to drop off students and exit onto Grove Street. As
the school’s arrival coincides with the weekday morning commuter peak period, the traffic
generated by the school has been included in the weekday morning capacity and queue analysis
School is dismissed at the Atrium School at 3:00 PM for grades K-5 and at 3:15 PM for grades 6-
8. During school dismissal, parents park along the residential streets surrounding the school to
wait for their children to be released. The school dismissal period occurs outside of the
weekday evening commuter peak period, which reduces the volume of traffic in the area during
the school dismissal period. In addition, the Atrium School offers a number of after school
programs, including child care, sports, music lessons, and other activities that continue until
5:30 PM and also reduce the volume of parent traffic during the school dismissal period. The
ATR counts collected on Grove Street south of Arlington Street indicate that traffic volumes in
the area around the Atrium School are approximately 27 percent lower during the school
dismissal period (2:30 to 3:30 PM) than during the weekday evening commuter peak period,
and approximately 36 percent lower during the school dismissal period than during the weekday
morning peak period. Therefore, the weekday morning and evening peak hours are the critical
time periods for analysis. Traffic operations during the school dismissal period are expected to
be significantly better than during the weekday morning and evening peak periods.
Although the 65 Grove Street and Atrium School driveways are located immediately adjacent to
each other, the 65 Grove Street driveway operates entrance-only, while the Atrium School
driveway operates exit-only. Therefore, these driveways essentially operate like a single access
point with entering and exiting movements separated by centerline or median. In addition,
there will be little traffic entering the 65 Grove Street driveway when traffic is exiting the school
driveway, as these sites will experience opposite trip distribution patterns. As a result, conflicts
between these driveways will be minimal.

page.text: The former GE Water and Process Technologies (GE) site previously accommodated
approximately 250 vehicles parked on the site. During this time, GE employed approximately
350 people on the site. Employees who could not be accommodated on the site would park in
on-street spaces along Crawford Street, Kondazian Street, and other residential neighborhoods
surrounding the site. Many of GE’s employees also carpooled or utilized public transportation
due to the shortage of available parking on the site.
In order to accommodate all site-related vehicles parked on the site and avoid impacts to the
surrounding neighborhood, a parking garage is proposed as part of the 65 Grove Street
Redevelopment project to allow for a total of 349 parking spaces on the site.
The Town of Watertown Zoning Regulations contains off-street parking supply requirements for
various land uses within the Town of Watertown. Based on zoning regulations for the
Industrial-3 Zoning District, a total of 320 parking spaces (1 space per 350 SF of gross floor
area for retail and office on ground floor and 1 space per 400 SF of gross floor area above the
ground floor) are required to serve the ±122,470 SF (Per Section §6.01(b)).
The proposed parking supply of 349 off-street spaces is adequate to meet Town of Watertown
Parking Zoning Ordinance for square footage and to accommodate all parking on-site to reduce
the impacts to the surrounding neighborhood.
